ChatGPT Review sentiment Analysis¶

Onkar Pednekar - Sentiment Analysis¶

Link to dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/charunisa/chatgpt-sentiment-analysis?resource=download

About the dataset:¶

The "ChatGPT Sentiment Analysis" dataset consists of tweets that mention ChatGPT, a well-known AI language model, and is labeled with sentiment scores that indicate whether each tweet is good, bador neutral in sentiment. The dataset presents a timely and pertinent issue for studying public attitude about this cutting-edge technology and consists of a significant amount of tweets. The dataset consists of 2 columns ie tweets and labels. The dataset is unstructured.

Why I chose the dataset:¶

I selected the "ChatGPT Sentiment Analysis" dataset because I was keen on finding out how people see ChatGPT and how it is utilized in different circumstances, which is why I was drawn to this dataset. Understanding how individuals feel about ChatGPT might help determine how the model should be improved or tailored to better suit user requirements.

This dataset also poses unique problems for sentiment analysis due to factors such as class imbalance and noise. Class imbalance may be an issue since there are quite a lot of posts with sentiment ratings of positive, negative, or neutral. There may be a big variation in how many tweets fall into each sentiment group. Additionally, noise like sarcasm, irony, or irrelevant tweets might make sentiment analysis more difficult. Despite these difficulties, the dataset offers a great chance for experimenting with and improving different NLP methods for dealing with noise and class imbalance. I decided to take on the task of working with this dataset because I wanted to learn more about how people feel about ChatGPT and come up with solutions to the problems it brings.

def remove_stopwords(tweets):
    stop_words = stopwords.words('english')
    data = [[word.lower() for word in word_tokenize(sent) if ((word.isalpha()) and word not in stop_words)] for sent in tqdm(tweets)]
    return data
data = remove_stopwords(tweets)
print(data[0])

In [6]:



     


def lemmatize(data):
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    tweets_pos = [nltk.pos_tag(tweet) for tweet in tqdm(data)]
    tweets_lemma = [[lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos=wordnet_pos(tag)) for word, tag in pos_tags] for pos_tags in tqdm(tweets_pos)]
    return tweets_lemma

def lemmatize_words(words, pos_tags):
    return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos=wordnet_pos(tag)) for word, tag in zip(words, pos_tags)]

def wordnet_pos(pos_tag):
    if pos_tag.startswith('J'):
        return wordnet.ADJ
    elif pos_tag.startswith('V'):
        return wordnet.VERB
    elif pos_tag.startswith('N'):
        return wordnet.NOUN
    elif pos_tag.startswith('R'):
        return wordnet.ADV
    else:
        return wordnet.NOUN

data = lemmatize(data)
print(data[0])

In [7]:



     


def get_TFIDF_vectors(tweets_lemma):
    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
    lists = [" ".join(row) for row in tweets_lemma]
    vectorizer.fit(lists)
    tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.transform(lists)
    X = tfidf_matrix.toarray()
    return vectorizer,X

vectorizer, X = get_TFIDF_vectors(data)
print(X)

def encodeLabels(y):
    encoder = LabelEncoder()
    encoder = encoder.fit(y)
    Y = encoder.transform(y)
    return encoder,Y

encoder, Y = encodeLabels(y)

In [14]:



     


def predictReview(review,vectorizer,encoder):
    reviewProcessed = remove_stopwords([review])
    reviewLemma = lemmatize(reviewProcessed)
    reviewTFIDF = vectorizer.transform([" ".join(word) for word in reviewLemma]).toarray()
    print('Shape of input review is: ', reviewTFIDF.shape)
    pred = model.predict(reviewTFIDF)
    pred = encoder.inverse_transform(pred).item()
    return pred
